context: 2010s saw multiple new sounds in house music developed by numerous DJs. Sweden knew a prominence of <a0_0><b5_0>snare-less<b5_0/><a0_0/> "Swedish progressive house" with the emergence of Sebastian Ingrosso, Axwell, Steve Angello (These three formed a trio called <a1_0><b6_0>Swedish House Mafia<b6_0/><a1_0/>), Avicii, Alesso, etc. Netherlands brought together a concept of "<a2_0><b7_0>Dirty Dutch<b7_0/><a2_0/>", electro house subgenre characterized by very abrasive leads and darker arpeggios, with prominent DJs Chuckie, Hardwell, Laidback Luke, Afrojack, R3hab, Bingo Players, Quintino, Alvaro, Cedric Gervais, 2G, etc. Elsewhere, fusion genres derivative of 2000s progressive house returned to prominence, especially with the help of DJs Calvin Harris, Eric Prydz, Mat Zo, Above & Beyond and Fonzerelli in Europe, Deadmau5, Kaskade, Steve Aoki, Porter Robinson and Wolfgang Gartner in the US and Canada. The growing popularity of such artists led to the emergence of electro house and progressive house blended sounds in popular music, such as singles <a3_0><b8_0>Lady Gaga<b8_0/><a3_0/>'s "Marry the Night", The Black Eyed Peas' "The Best One Yet (The Boy)" and the will.i.am and Britney Spears "Scream & Shout". Big room house found increasing popularity since <a4_0><b9_0>2010<b9_0/><a4_0/>, particularly through international dance music festivals such as Tomorrowland, Ultra Music Festival, and Electric Daisy Carnival.
